explanation:
Each symbol is needed to decide whether any executed operations in OS_FileSysMountVolume_Impl are dead (i.e., can be removed without affecting program behaviour):

- OS_object_token_t: type of the token parameter; needed to know if dereferencing (*token) or passing it to table access has side effects or constraints that affect reachability/behaviour.
- OS_filesys_table: the object/table passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Its layout or accessor semantics could introduce side effects or determine which record is returned.
- OS_filesys_internal_record_t: structure type of 'local'; must know the semantics and possible values of its fields (system_mountpt, fstype) to determine which branches (mkdir, error returns, final success) can occur.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/function used to obtain 'local'. Its implementation may call other functions (e.g., OS_ObjectIndexFromToken), perform checks, or have side effects that affect whether subsequent code is dead.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: shown in the static call graph as a callee related to object-table access. Needed to see if obtaining the object index has side effects (error returns, assertions) that make parts of this function unreachable or necessary.
- struct stat: type of stat_buf; must know fields (st_mode etc.) and layout to interpret S_ISDIR check and to see if stat use is meaningful.
- S_ISDIR: macro used to test stat_buf.st_mode; determines when the error path (exists and not a directory) executes — crucial to decide if that branch can occur.
- stat: system/library call used to detect existence/type of mount point; its semantics determine whether the mkdir path is reachable and whether removing that code would change behaviour.
- mkdir: system/library call creating the mount point; has side effects (filesystem changes). Required to judge whether the mkdir code is dead.
- strerror: used by OS_DEBUG to produce a string. Needed to determine whether the call in the error-reporting expression has side effects relevant to behaviour/observability.
- errno: global errno read by strerror; used to decide observable error details — affects program behaviour (diagnostics) and thus whether the code is dead.
- OS_DEBUG: logging/debug macro or function invoked on error. Its implementation determines whether the call has side effects (I/O, state changes) or is compile-time no-op; this affects dead-code determination for the error-reporting lines.
- OS_FS_ERR_DRIVE_NOT_CREATED: return code used on mount-point creation or wrong-type errors. Required to see whether returning this value affects program behaviour (callers) and thus whether the return statements are semantically necessary.
- OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED: return code used when fstype is not supported. Needed to determine whether that branch is meaningful and affects callers.
- OS_FILESYS_TYPE_VOLATILE_DISK: one fstype value checked; must know whether local->fstype can equal this to see if the non-implemented return is reachable.
- OS_FILESYS_TYPE_FS_BASED: the other fstype value treated as supported; required to evaluate branch conditions and whether the non-implemented path can be removed.
- OS_SUCCESS: final return value; needed to know whether returning success is necessary for callers and to determine if earlier returns are dead relative to this final return.

In short, these symbols provide the type/layout information, side-effect semantics, macros and constants that determine which branches are reachable and which operations have externally observable effects. Without them one cannot conclude whether any executed operation in this function is removable without changing program behaviour (i.e., whether it is dead code).
